*   Notify the family immediately. [Section 2.5]
*   Record the incident (time, place, symptoms, and actions taken). [Section 2.5]
*   Ensure the child is taken to hospital, even if symptoms improve. [Section 2.5]

3. FINAL ANSWER: Upon a student collapsing after eating lunch and showing signs of a severe allergic reaction, staff should immediately call 112 and administer self-injectable adrenaline if reported by the family and available at the school. [Section 2.5] If the child is conscious, place them lying down with legs elevated. [Section 2.5] Do not leave the child unattended until medical assistance arrives. [Section 2.5] Only trained first aiders should administer first aid, and the person who finds the child will deal with the medical emergency immediately. [Section 2.4] All staff should be aware of students with severe allergies and be alert to the need for prompt action. [Section 2.4] The family should be notified immediately, and the incident (time, place, symptoms, and actions taken) must be recorded. [Section 2.5] Ensure the child is taken to hospital, even if symptoms improve. [Section 2.5]

